<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="522" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d522">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/938.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-22">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 22, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My June 20.* * * The President has moved about two thousand men to Saint
                            Marc. Port au Prince is quiet and the Commission appointed to act with
                            the Cabinet is regarded as a very good one. However, there is much
                            apprehension expressed on the streets.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
